"Demek J.","Global warming and permafrost in Eurasia: a catastrophic scenario",1994,"Geomorphology","10","1-4",,"317","329",,,10.1016/0169-555X(94)90023-X,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0028577089&partnerID=40&md5=16f80b7ab5d528d6915c681e346df0a5","Palacký University, Faculty of Sciences, 771 46 Olomouc, Czech Republic","Demek, J., Palacký University, Faculty of Sciences, 771 46 Olomouc, Czech Republic","Since models of global warming predict that climatic changes will be greatest in the Arctic and might already be in progress, it is prudent to attempt to understand the rapidly changing thermal régime on Eurasia cold regions. In this paper the author tries to evaluate the probable catastrophic implications of global climatic change in the cold regions of Eurasia. The impact on Man activities in permafrost regions is discussed. © 1994.",,"climate change; global warming; permafrost; Eurasia",,,,,,"Bolle, Das System Erde (1993) Geogr. Rundsch., 45 (2), pp. 81-87; Czudek, Demek, Thermokarst in Siberia and its Influence on the development of lowland relief (1970) Quat. Res., 1 (1), pp. 103-120; Embleton, King, (1975) Periglacial Geomorphology, p. 203. , Edward Arnold, London; Farley, That sinking feeling (1991) Geogr. Mag., 63 (2), pp. 36-39; Flohn, Das CO2-Klima-Problem (1983) Geogr. Rundsch., 35 (5), pp. 238-247; French, (1974) The Periglacial Environment, p. 309. , Longman, London; Haeberli, Permafrost-glacier relationships in the Swiss Alps, today and in the past (1983) Proc. Third Int. Conf. on Permafrost, 1, pp. 415-420. , Nat. Ac. Press, Washington, DC; Hansen, Lacis, Rind, Russel, Stone, Fung, Ruedy, Lerner, Climate sensitivity: analysis of feedback mechanism (1984) Climate Processes and Climate Sensitivity, pp. 130-163. , J. Hansen, T. Takahashi, Maurice Ewing Series, 5, American Geophysical Union, Washington, DC; King, Gorbunov, Evin, Prospecting and mapping of mountain permafrost and associated phenomena (1992) Permafrost and Periglacial P